sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1230016
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
General Design Our design has two systems: The Antimicrobial Peptide System, which produces the peptide LL-37; and The Resistance and Expulsion System which produces the MarA protein, which activates the arcAB & TolC operons, activating the arcAB & TolC efflux pump.
Antimicrobial Peptide System H. pylori and other pathogenic bacteria produce AI-2, a quorum sensing molecule. This signal is detected by the pLsrA promoter (BBa_K117002), which allows the transcription of LL37 (BBa_K1230001), which is traduced and then translated into the antimicrobial peptide LL37. Once LL37 is expelled by the ArcAB-TolC efflux pump, it can act against H. pylori.
Resistance & Expulsion System This system is induced by promoter LacI (BBa_R0010), which allows the transcription of marA gene (BBa_K1230000), producing the protein MarA. MarA acts on the arcAB and tolC operons, which activates de ArcAB-TolC efflux pump, allowing the expulsion of LL37 peptide.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andr??s Ferri??o Iriarte
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: LL-37 has the codon usage for humans. Using E. coli codon usage may inhibit protein function by wrong folding.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1230012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: LL37 Generator under pLsrA promoter, with part BBa_E0840 as prefix.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andr??s Ferri??o Iriarte
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This is an intermediate part. It can be used to produce an antimicrobial peptide in the presence of AI-2, a quorum-sensing molecule.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1230004
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
The MarA protein acts as a transcriptional activator in E. coli. It allows the expression of the acrAB and tolC operons, which activate the AcrAB-TolC efflux pump, a mechanism that has been related with resistance to organic solvents, dyes, detergents, antibiotics such as chloramphenicol, tetracycline, novobiocin, erythromycin, fusidic acid and cloxacillin, as well as to cationic antimicrobial peptides, such as LL-37, HNP-2 and HBD-1.
This composite part allows MarA expression in presence of IPTG, by using the LacI promoter and the RBS based on Elowitz repressilator (Part BBa_J04500)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andr??s Ferri??o Iriarte
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: 2013 DNA distribution and synthesis by genscript.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We ligated part BBa_K875009 as a prefix and part BBa_E0840 as a suffix.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1230008
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: LL-37 antimicrobial peptide generator with codon usage for E. coli, under the arabinose promoter with a GFP generator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andr??s Ferri??o Iriarte
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: LL-37 has the codon usage for E. coli, this could change the folding activities of the peptide.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: LacI
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Inverting regulatory region controlled by LacI (BBa_C0010, BBa_C0011, etc.)

The pLac regulatory region is a 243 base-pair sequence with standard BioBrick prefix and suffix sections on its ends. It contains two protein binding sites: CAP, which is generally present in E.coli and is assocciated with cell health and availability of glucose., and LacI, the Lac inhibitor BBa_C0010 which binds in an dimerized cooperative manner to inhibit the transcription of the protein that follows. In the presence of lactose or IPTG, an analog of lactose, LacI is unable to correctly bind and inhibit transcription. This allows BBa_R0010 to be used as a inverter or as a detector of lactose or IPTG.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The Plac insert was PCR'd from the MG1655 strain of E.coli K12.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: LacI binds to this regulator. This part is incompatible with species containing active LacI coding regions. Lactose and IPTG disable the operation of LacI and this regulator. This part is incompatible with environments containing lactose or lactose analogs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: RBS based on Elowitz repressilator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K117002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
The regulatory network for the uptake of Escherichia coli autoinducer 2 (AI-2) is comprised of a transporter complex, LsrABCD; its repressor, LsrR; and a cognate signal kinase, LsrK. This network is an integral part of the AI-2 quorum-sensing (QS) system. Once uptaken into the cell, AI-2 will be phosphorylated under the effect of LsrK. Without the presence of AI-2, LsrA promoter is inhibited by the repressor, LsrR. Phosphorylated AI-2 will prevent LsrR from inhibiting this promoter, hence activating it so that the downstream sequence can be expressed. To prevent the cell from self-inducing this promoter, we must suppress its AI-2 producing capability. It can be done by knocking out LuxS, one of the vital gene required for producing AI-2. By doing that, LsrA promoter can only be activated under the presence of AI-2 from other sources than the host cell which is LuxS mutant (say, by contact with normal cells).
More information on AI-2 quorum-sensing (QS) system please refer to: http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?artid=1952038
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Nguyen Xuan Hung
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: to be updated

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: LL-37
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The human peptide LL-37 is a cationic antimicrobial peptide with activity against Gram-negative and Gram-positive bacteria. It has been shown to protect against Helicobacter pylori infection and its related gastritis, besides of inhibiting the growth of other pathogenic bacteria in the gastrointestinal tract such as Salmonella typhimurium and Escherichia coli.
